This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it discusses a Python library that provides a unified interface to nonnegative matrix factorization algorithms. It could also belong to the information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as matrix factorization is often used in recommendation systems. The library's support for both dense and sparse matrix representation suggests it could also be relevant to the data structures (cs.DS) sub-category. Additionally, the library's quality scoring feature could make it relevant to the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the library's potential use in computer vision applications could make it relevant to the computer vision and pattern recognition (cs.CV) sub-category.
